Lab 01 - Data Cleaning¶

Paige Rosynek, 12.6.2022

Introduction¶

In this lab, we will be exploring the process of loading, analyzing, and cleaning a dataset. The dataset we will be using contains real estate transaction data from properties located in Sacremento, California. The goal of this lab is to gain familiarity with the Pandas library, as well as produce a "cleaned" version of the original dataset. Throughout this lab, we will be using data visualization as well as statistical summaries to communicate trends and findings in the dataset to support our analysis.

It can be observed from the table that the last token in a street address is usually the street type. However, for addresses that have unit numbers, the street type is the third to last token in the address. For addresses with 'HIGHWAY' as the street type end in a digit so the second to last token is the street type. In addition, there are some addresses that do not have a street type or the street type is given in Spanish.

Write a function get_street_type(address) that will return the street type (as a string) of an address

In [ ]:
def get_street_type(address):
    address = address.upper()
    tokens = address.split(" ")
    
    street_type = tokens[-1]
    
    if tokens[-2] == 'UNIT':
        street_type = tokens[-3]
    elif tokens[-1].isdigit():
        street_type = tokens[-2]
    elif tokens[1] == 'AVENIDA' or tokens[1] == 'VISTA':
        street_type = tokens[1]
    
        
    return str(street_type)

Use that function to create a new categorical variable of street types

In [ ]:
df['street_type'] = df['street'].apply(get_street_type).astype('category')

In general, integer valued columns are most likely good candidates for regression problems and categorical variables are good candidates for classfication problems. The variable price would be good output variable for a regression problem because it is an integer type and depends on the values of the other features. The variable 'type' would be a good output variable for a classification problem because it is a categorical variable and has only a few unique values to represent clases.

Conclusion¶

Throughout this lab, I was able to gain experience and a better understanding of the process of data cleaning. After analyzing the Sacremento dataset, we found that Pandas may not always infer the correct data types for columns when loading in the data, so we converted some of the columns like city, state, zip, beds, bath, and type to categorical variables. From plotting each of these variables with a bar chart we were able to gain insight into the number of occurrences of certain values for each column. The beds, baths, and sq_ft columns had some values that were 0, which in the context of our problem meant that the entry most likely represented an empty plot or a non-residential property. Thus, we added a new categorical column called 'empty_lot' that is true for any entry that has a square footage (sq_ft) of 0. One takeaway from this lab was that although there were no null values in the dataset, there was still outliers in our dataset that we had to remove; like in step 8 where we removed the data entry with the 'type' value of 'Unkown'. After completing the analysis of the data, it was concluded that this data set would work for a regression or classification problem to train a ML model. Categorical features make better candidates for classification problems and integer or float values make good candidates for regression problems.
